augmentation_prompt_templates.prompt:
My agent instruction files contain {count} file(s) with unresolved reference(s) to other skills/rules:
{items}

Each bullet is `referring_file -> missing_target` (the target name/slug that does not resolve in the on-disk inventory). For each one: confirm whether the target skill/rule exists under a different path (e.g. `skills/<name>/SKILL.md`), then either fix the reference path or remove the stale reference. Do NOT rewrite unrelated short rule-to-rule links. Show me a diff for each file before applying.

These skills were invoked in my agent sessions but have no file on disk in this workspace ({count} total):
{items}

For each, check whether it lives in another workspace or was deleted. If it is genuinely useful here, recreate it as a proper skill file (SKILL.md or rule) in this workspace; otherwise tell me why it keeps being referenced.

These instruction artifacts overlap heavily in content ({count} cluster(s)):
{items}

For each cluster, compare the files, merge them into one canonical skill keeping the best parts of each, update anything that references the removed copies, and delete the redundant files. Show me the merged content before deleting anything.

These always-loaded instruction files dominate my standing per-prompt token cost ({count} hotspot(s)):
{items}

Rewrite each to be dramatically shorter: keep only invariants and hard constraints inline, move examples, walkthroughs and reference material into on-demand skill files, and delete anything the codebase itself already documents. Target at least a 50% token reduction per file. Show diffs before applying.

These on-demand skills were never invoked and have no description/frontmatter, so agents cannot discover them ({count} total):
{items}

For each, read the skill body and write a one-sentence trigger-oriented description (when should an agent reach for this?) in its frontmatter. If the skill is obsolete, propose deleting it instead.

These on-demand skills exist on disk but were never used in the observation window ({count} total):
{items}

For each, judge from its content whether it is still relevant to this codebase. Propose keep / improve-description / merge / delete, then apply the agreed actions.

These instruction files scored low on structural authoring quality ({count} total):
{items}

For each: add proper frontmatter (name + trigger description), a clear task contract, concrete examples, and split anything over ~200 lines into focused sub-skills. Show me a before/after summary per file.

These {count} skill(s)/command(s) were used from workspace {workspace} and also from other workspaces (cross-workspace reuse):
{items}

Propose a consolidation plan: pick a canonical home (shared agent-level skill vs one workspace copy), list which duplicates to remove or redirect, and preserve capability. Apply changes only after I confirm.
